00:00:39.820 --> 00:00:41.400
On the thermodynamic framework
we've been

00:00:41.400 --> 00:00:42.740
working with all term.

00:00:42.740 --> 00:00:45.940
But you saw them derived from
a microscopic perspective.

00:00:45.940 --> 00:00:50.060
Now what I want to do is move
to examples that are more

00:00:50.060 --> 00:00:52.000
commonly encountered
in chemistry.

00:00:52.000 --> 00:00:55.860
One that we did last time
actually was very common, or

00:00:55.860 --> 00:00:58.070
is at least a prototype
for something common.

00:00:58.070 --> 00:01:02.275
That is we looked at what would
be a simple model for a

00:01:02.275 --> 00:01:03.980
polymer with different
configurations

00:01:03.980 --> 00:01:05.310
available to it.

00:01:05.310 --> 00:01:08.550
And just tried to understand
what the basic thermodynamics

00:01:08.550 --> 00:01:09.240
is that it would exhibit.

00:01:09.240 --> 00:01:12.590
What the heat capacities would
be in various limiting cases.

00:01:12.590 --> 00:01:14.320
High and low temperature.

00:01:14.320 --> 00:01:16.180
I want to continue that today.

00:01:16.180 --> 00:01:18.090
But for an even more
common case.

00:01:18.090 --> 00:01:23.480
So the model that I want to lay
out is indicated on your

00:01:23.480 --> 00:01:25.540
notes for today.

00:01:25.540 --> 00:01:28.440
And essentially, you
could look at it as

00:01:28.440 --> 00:01:30.370
double stranded DNA.

00:01:30.370 --> 00:01:33.850
Any kind of polymer with
a whole variety of

00:01:33.850 --> 00:01:34.950
configurations.

00:01:34.950 --> 00:01:39.150
Ultimately what's going to
matter is what is the set of

00:01:39.150 --> 00:01:42.170
energy levels available
to the system.

00:01:42.170 --> 00:01:44.480
And so here's what
it looks like.

00:01:44.480 --> 00:01:48.700
The way I've tried
to depict it.

00:01:48.700 --> 00:01:57.420
I'm imagining something like,
covalently bonded chains that

00:01:57.420 --> 00:01:58.690
have links between them.

00:01:58.690 --> 00:02:03.250
So of course, it's reminiscent
of DNA with hydrogen bonding

00:02:03.250 --> 00:02:05.770
between the strands.

00:02:05.770 --> 00:02:09.910
And the idea in this simple
model is that you can have

00:02:09.910 --> 00:02:13.110
various numbers of these
hydrogen bonds.

00:02:13.110 --> 00:02:15.890
So this is the case that
would be the most

00:02:15.890 --> 00:02:16.980
energetically stable.

00:02:16.980 --> 00:02:20.010
That is, all the available
hydrogen bonds are formed

00:02:20.010 --> 00:02:22.930
between neighboring pairs.

00:02:22.930 --> 00:02:26.570
So this would be our
lowest energy.

00:02:26.570 --> 00:02:29.890
Now let's starts breaking
some hydrogen bonds.

00:02:29.890 --> 00:02:34.020
And what I'm imagining is they
break starting at one end and

00:02:34.020 --> 00:02:35.110
working their way down.

00:02:35.110 --> 00:02:52.370
So the next highest energy
state would be like this.

00:02:52.370 --> 00:02:54.610
So now these are still
hydrogen bonded.

00:02:54.610 --> 00:02:55.980
This is not.

00:02:55.980 --> 00:02:58.040
And there's a cost in
energy for breaking

00:02:58.040 --> 00:03:01.140
that hydrogen bond.

00:03:01.140 --> 00:03:04.910
We'll call it epsilon zero.

00:03:04.910 --> 00:03:06.340
It's a positive number.

00:03:06.340 --> 00:03:09.100
So that this is higher
energy than this.

00:03:09.100 --> 00:03:15.500
And now we'll go to the next
one, which could have two

00:03:15.500 --> 00:03:17.440
broken bonds.

00:03:17.440 --> 00:03:26.980
Broken hydrogen bonds.

00:03:26.980 --> 00:03:27.580
And so on.

00:03:27.580 --> 00:03:29.990
And if we imagine that this is
very long, there may be many

00:03:29.990 --> 00:03:31.320
many, members of the chain.

00:03:31.320 --> 00:03:35.030
Then of course this sequence
of structures with

00:03:35.030 --> 00:03:39.360
corresponding energies might
go on for a very long way.

00:03:39.360 --> 00:03:42.500
So this is a simple construction
that gives us a

00:03:42.500 --> 00:03:47.670
set of states with distinct
energies.

00:03:47.670 --> 00:03:56.340
And so we have a series of
configurational energy levels.

00:03:56.340 --> 00:03:59.990
They're evenly spaced
in this model.

00:03:59.990 --> 00:04:09.780
So there's zero, E
zero, two E zero.

00:04:09.780 --> 00:04:15.530
And so on.

00:04:15.530 --> 00:04:18.630
So those are available
energy states.

00:04:18.630 --> 00:04:21.920
And now, just based on that
simple model, we should be

00:04:21.920 --> 00:04:23.570
able to figure out all
the thermodynamics.

00:04:23.570 --> 00:04:25.620
We should should be able
to figure out what the

00:04:25.620 --> 00:04:28.710
equilibrium energy is at a
particular temperature.

00:04:28.710 --> 00:04:30.230
What the average energy is.

00:04:30.230 --> 00:04:33.330
And so forth.

00:04:33.330 --> 00:04:39.150
And we can do it in a
straightforward way.

00:04:39.150 --> 00:04:47.440
So we'll start with our
molecular partition

00:04:47.440 --> 00:04:50.230
function, as always.

00:04:50.230 --> 00:04:53.920
So it's q configurational.

00:04:53.920 --> 00:04:57.300
And it's just a sum over our
available states with their

00:04:57.300 --> 00:04:59.240
associated Boltzmann factors.

00:04:59.240 --> 00:05:05.170
So sum over n of e to the
minus En over kT.

00:05:05.170 --> 00:05:10.110
Now the way I've modeled this,
there are no degeneracies.

00:05:10.110 --> 00:05:14.660
Each energy level has just one
microscopic state of the

00:05:14.660 --> 00:05:16.280
molecule corresponding to it.

00:05:16.280 --> 00:05:20.240
So there are no molecular
degeneracies.

00:05:20.240 --> 00:05:22.840
Turns out we'll be able to put
this into a simple form.

00:05:22.840 --> 00:05:28.110
So the first thing is, let's
approximate that we could take

00:05:28.110 --> 00:05:31.920
the sum -- not to some finite
level, which would be the case

00:05:31.920 --> 00:05:34.900
if there's a finite number
of elements in the chain.

00:05:34.900 --> 00:05:48.660
But all the way through
infinity.

00:05:48.660 --> 00:05:52.560
And the idea here is
the following.

00:05:52.560 --> 00:05:54.160
We'll assume that the
chain at least has

00:05:54.160 --> 00:05:56.140
a great many members.

00:05:56.140 --> 00:05:58.590
Even if it's finite.

00:05:58.590 --> 00:06:04.140
And then at some point, this
becomes a really small number.

00:06:04.140 --> 00:06:07.840
Even if epsilon naught, the
energy of one of the bonds, is

00:06:07.840 --> 00:06:09.650
less than kT.

00:06:09.650 --> 00:06:13.530
Once we multiply it by a very
large number n, it becomes

00:06:13.530 --> 00:06:15.320
very much greater than kT.

00:06:15.320 --> 00:06:19.200
So the underlying assumption
here is, well there will not

00:06:19.200 --> 00:06:22.600
be a significant number of
molecules in the highest

00:06:22.600 --> 00:06:24.790
energy state anyway.

00:06:24.790 --> 00:06:30.150
In other words, the terms higher
than a finite but large

00:06:30.150 --> 00:06:34.200
value of n between there and
infinity are going to be so

00:06:34.200 --> 00:06:38.585
small that those terms will
contribute negligibly to the

00:06:38.585 --> 00:06:40.990
sum anyway.

00:06:40.990 --> 00:06:43.280
And on that basis, we could
make this approximation.

00:06:43.280 --> 00:06:45.730
And the incentive to make this
approximation and carry the

00:06:45.730 --> 00:06:48.860
sum to infinity is that then we
can put this in what turns

00:06:48.860 --> 00:06:52.060
out to be a very simple
closed form.

00:06:52.060 --> 00:06:56.280
So now if we just write out a
few of the individual terms in

00:06:56.280 --> 00:06:59.450
the sum, it's one plus
e to the minus

00:06:59.450 --> 00:07:02.330
epsilon zero over kT.

00:07:02.330 --> 00:07:08.240
Plus e to the minus epsilon
zero over kT.

00:07:08.240 --> 00:07:10.520
I'll write this as squared.
e to the minus two

00:07:10.520 --> 00:07:12.670
epsilon zero over k t.

00:07:12.670 --> 00:07:13.830
And so on.

00:07:13.830 --> 00:07:19.330
So this has the form of a sum
that looks like one plus x,

00:07:19.330 --> 00:07:21.970
plus x squared, and so on.

00:07:21.970 --> 00:07:25.450
And because the sum goes to
infinity, we can simply write

00:07:25.450 --> 00:07:30.630
it as one over one minus x.

00:07:30.630 --> 00:07:32.590
Sort of a very simple result.

00:07:32.590 --> 00:07:38.550
And now putting this back into
x, it's one over one minus e

00:07:38.550 --> 00:07:43.290
to the minus epsilon
zero over kT.

00:07:43.290 --> 00:07:45.450
That's our q zero.

00:07:45.450 --> 00:07:51.140
Our molecular partition
function.

00:07:51.140 --> 00:07:53.860
So this model yields a
particularly simple

00:07:53.860 --> 00:07:55.740
result for q zero.

00:07:55.740 --> 00:07:59.360
And then everything else
follows from there.

00:07:59.360 --> 00:08:12.430
So then we can write the
canonical partition function

00:08:12.430 --> 00:08:13.420
capital Qn.

00:08:13.420 --> 00:08:21.100
It's just q configurational to
the capital Nth power, where

00:08:21.100 --> 00:08:25.690
capital N is the total number
of these molecules.

00:08:25.690 --> 00:08:29.640
So it's just one over one minus
e to the minus epsilon

00:08:29.640 --> 00:08:35.930
over kT to the Nth power.

00:08:35.930 --> 00:08:38.190
And then we can start writing
out the results for the

00:08:38.190 --> 00:08:39.940
various thermodynamic
properties.

00:08:39.940 --> 00:08:54.140
So A configurational is minus
NkT, log q configurational.

00:08:54.140 --> 00:09:03.150
That is, remember, A is minus kT
log capital Q. And this is

00:09:03.150 --> 00:09:05.410
just going to come
straight out.

00:09:05.410 --> 00:09:10.850
So it's minus NkT
log of little q.

00:09:10.850 --> 00:09:17.240
Minus NkT, log of one over
one minus e to the minus

00:09:17.240 --> 00:09:19.950
epsilon over kT.

00:09:19.950 --> 00:09:26.880
Or positive NkT, log of one
minus e to the minus

00:09:26.880 --> 00:09:30.140
epsilon over kT.

00:09:30.140 --> 00:09:35.010
So a pretty simple form for
the Helmholtz free energy.

00:09:35.010 --> 00:09:37.790
And I'm not going to write out
all of the individuals

00:09:37.790 --> 00:09:40.510
thermodynamic terms, but I'll
write a few of them.

00:09:40.510 --> 00:09:46.485
So mu, the chemical potential
for these configurations, is

00:09:46.485 --> 00:09:47.735
just dA/dN.

00:09:53.100 --> 00:09:54.190
With T and V constant.

00:09:54.190 --> 00:09:57.030
And so the only capital
N dependence, the only

00:09:57.030 --> 00:10:00.490
dependence on the number of
molecules is multiplicative.

00:10:00.490 --> 00:10:03.320
Right here.

00:10:03.320 --> 00:10:08.750
So this just gives us kT log
of one minus e to the minus

00:10:08.750 --> 00:10:10.820
epsilon naught over kT.

00:10:10.820 --> 00:10:12.980
And the important point to
realize here that we mentioned

00:10:12.980 --> 00:10:15.830
last time too, in the examples
we considered then, especially

00:10:15.830 --> 00:10:21.750
the last one, is that because
the only place that N figures

00:10:21.750 --> 00:10:26.050
in is as a multiplicative
factor.

00:10:26.050 --> 00:10:29.490
What this is telling us is that
we just have a chemical

00:10:29.490 --> 00:10:33.180
potential, of Helmholtz free
energy per molecule.

00:10:33.180 --> 00:10:35.910
The molecules are
all independent.

00:10:35.910 --> 00:10:38.140
The total energy doesn't depend
on any interaction

00:10:38.140 --> 00:10:42.530
between this molecule and its
neighbor somewhere else.

00:10:42.530 --> 00:10:45.750
So terms like this are
simply additive.

00:10:45.750 --> 00:10:48.420
So if we work out the chemical
potential, it's just one over

00:10:48.420 --> 00:10:56.120
N times A.

00:10:56.120 --> 00:11:04.410
And I'll just write the result
for u configurational.

00:11:04.410 --> 00:11:08.040
Because I do want to look
at the heat capacity.

00:11:08.040 --> 00:11:22.670
So it's Nk T squared, d log of
little q configurational / dT.

00:11:22.670 --> 00:11:25.590
With N and V held constant.

00:11:25.590 --> 00:11:31.310
And it turns out to just
be N epsilon zero.

00:11:31.310 --> 00:11:40.770
One over E zero over
kT minus one.

00:11:40.770 --> 00:11:43.930
So now we can look at
the heat capacity.

00:11:43.930 --> 00:11:49.030
Cv configurational.

00:11:49.030 --> 00:11:54.590
So it's du configurational
/ dT.

00:11:54.590 --> 00:11:59.420
With constant N and V. And
taking this derivative with

00:11:59.420 --> 00:12:02.600
respect to temperature.

00:12:02.600 --> 00:12:05.160
Gives us an expression of
the following form.

00:12:05.160 --> 00:12:16.920
It's Nk epsilon zero over k T
squared. e to the E zero over

00:12:16.920 --> 00:12:24.460
kT, over e to the E zero over
kT minus one squared.

00:12:24.460 --> 00:12:27.480
Just taking the derivative
in the usual way.

00:12:27.480 --> 00:12:31.530
Now, this looks kind
of complicated

00:12:31.530 --> 00:12:33.360
for the heat capacity.

00:12:33.360 --> 00:12:36.330
But let's take a look, just like
we did last time for the

00:12:36.330 --> 00:12:39.130
simpler case that we treated
then, let's take a look at the

00:12:39.130 --> 00:12:42.800
high and low temperature limits
of what happens to the

00:12:42.800 --> 00:12:44.010
heat capacity.

00:12:44.010 --> 00:12:59.740
So at high temperature, well we
can start by just looking

00:12:59.740 --> 00:13:01.100
at the energy.

00:13:01.100 --> 00:13:03.570
That has a form that's
fairly simple.

00:13:03.570 --> 00:13:07.790
So when temperature is large,
this is small, and we can

00:13:07.790 --> 00:13:09.950
Taylor expand it.

00:13:09.950 --> 00:13:12.130
So then we're just going to
have one plus epsilon zero

00:13:12.130 --> 00:13:14.010
over kT minus one.

00:13:14.010 --> 00:13:16.160
Which means the ones
will cancel.

00:13:16.160 --> 00:13:18.450
And we end up with a fairly
simple result.

00:13:18.450 --> 00:13:24.830
So u configurational, in
that case, is just NkT.

00:13:28.180 --> 00:13:31.580
The epsilon zeroes are
going to cancel also.

00:13:31.580 --> 00:13:34.200
And what that says is that the
heat capacity -- and of course

00:13:34.200 --> 00:13:36.720
we could take the limit of this,
but we can just take the

00:13:36.720 --> 00:13:38.090
derivative of this
with respect to

00:13:38.090 --> 00:13:40.850
temperature more easily.

00:13:40.850 --> 00:13:45.230
So Cv configurational.

00:13:45.230 --> 00:13:47.340
It's just N times k.

00:13:47.340 --> 00:13:50.450
In other words, the heat
capacity in the high

00:13:50.450 --> 00:13:53.480
temperature limit
is a constant.

00:13:53.480 --> 00:13:56.430
Last time we treated a simpler
case, where there were only

00:13:56.430 --> 00:14:01.930
four configurations altogether
available, to this sort of

00:14:01.930 --> 00:14:04.490
simple polymer model
that we drew.

00:14:04.490 --> 00:14:08.330
Unlike this present model where
we're saying there are

00:14:08.330 --> 00:14:12.510
essentially infinite number of
configurations and different

00:14:12.510 --> 00:14:14.240
energies available.

00:14:14.240 --> 00:14:17.420
So many that the highest ones
we're never even going to

00:14:17.420 --> 00:14:21.420
access, because they'll be
much higher than kT.

00:14:21.420 --> 00:14:23.760
Here it's different,
so now we have --

00:14:23.760 --> 00:14:27.620
You know before, when we had
a limited number of total

00:14:27.620 --> 00:14:31.980
states, remember what happened
in the heat capacity at high

00:14:31.980 --> 00:14:32.420
temperature.

00:14:32.420 --> 00:14:34.910
What was the limiting case?

00:14:34.910 --> 00:14:36.920
Finite number of states.

00:14:36.920 --> 00:14:41.710
What's the heat capacity
at high temperature?

00:14:41.710 --> 00:14:45.180
This is going to
be on the exam.

00:14:45.180 --> 00:14:47.750
What's the heat capacity at high
temperature, if there's a

00:14:47.750 --> 00:14:49.540
finite number of states
available?

00:14:49.540 --> 00:14:50.660
STUDENT: Zero.

00:14:50.660 --> 00:14:52.310
PROFESSOR: It's zero.

00:14:52.310 --> 00:14:57.550
What was the low temperature
limit of the heat capacity?

00:14:57.550 --> 00:14:57.670
STUDENT: Zero.

00:14:57.670 --> 00:14:58.700
PROFESSOR: It was also zero.

00:14:58.700 --> 00:14:59.180
Right.

00:14:59.180 --> 00:15:05.980
And the idea was for
a system with a

00:15:05.980 --> 00:15:11.510
finite number of states.

00:15:11.510 --> 00:15:15.010
The idea was -- so let's say,
the way we had it before,

00:15:15.010 --> 00:15:16.970
there was one state
with energy zero.

00:15:16.970 --> 00:15:20.290
And we had three states with
some energy epsilon zero.

00:15:20.290 --> 00:15:21.840
And that was it.

00:15:21.840 --> 00:15:24.500
Those were all the molecular
states available.

00:15:24.500 --> 00:15:27.960
So we looked at the two cases.

00:15:27.960 --> 00:15:31.130
In one case, when the high
temperature limit where kT is

00:15:31.130 --> 00:15:33.640
much bigger than any
of this stuff.

00:15:33.640 --> 00:15:38.990
In that limit, the molecules are
just equally likely to be

00:15:38.990 --> 00:15:40.560
in any of these states.

00:15:40.560 --> 00:15:43.260
Because there's much, much more
thermal energy than this

00:15:43.260 --> 00:15:44.130
energy difference.

00:15:44.130 --> 00:15:45.860
And the molecules are constantly
getting kicked

00:15:45.860 --> 00:15:48.960
around by the available
thermal energy.

00:15:48.960 --> 00:15:51.940
So if you raise the temperature
a little bit more,

00:15:51.940 --> 00:15:53.320
it doesn't make any
difference.

00:15:53.320 --> 00:15:54.800
The molecules already
are evenly

00:15:54.800 --> 00:15:57.260
distributed among the states.

00:15:57.260 --> 00:16:00.080
There's no additional
configurational energy.

00:16:00.080 --> 00:16:03.480
So du/dT is zero.

00:16:03.480 --> 00:16:06.640
It can't increase any more.

00:16:06.640 --> 00:16:09.090
So in that case, the high
temperature limiting heat

00:16:09.090 --> 00:16:11.950
capacity is zero.

00:16:11.950 --> 00:16:19.240
And in the other case --

00:16:19.240 --> 00:16:21.640
In the low temperature
limit, now let's say

00:16:21.640 --> 00:16:22.640
kT is really low.

00:16:22.640 --> 00:16:24.700
It's much less than
epsilon zero.

00:16:24.700 --> 00:16:26.900
So now we'll redraw
this as zero.

00:16:26.900 --> 00:16:36.940
And put the epsilon zero
states up here.

00:16:36.940 --> 00:16:39.740
And kT is here.

00:16:39.740 --> 00:16:43.710
Well when it's like this, the
temperature is so low that

00:16:43.710 --> 00:16:46.240
there's not nearly enough
thermal energy to populate any

00:16:46.240 --> 00:16:47.420
of these states.

00:16:47.420 --> 00:16:49.320
And if you change the
temperature by a little bit,

