vibrations.

00:33:46.030 --> 00:33:51.590
And not only molecular
vibrations, but vibrations of

00:33:51.590 --> 00:33:57.000
a crystal lattice.

00:33:57.000 --> 00:34:00.440
Acoustic vibrations
of a glass.

00:34:00.440 --> 00:34:02.380
Or even a liquid.

00:34:02.380 --> 00:34:07.140
So there's an enormously wide
ranging set of results that

00:34:07.140 --> 00:34:13.020
we've derived by starting
at this simple picture.

00:34:13.020 --> 00:34:15.670
And when you take quantum
mechanics, you'll see that

00:34:15.670 --> 00:34:19.250
indeed you do get this set of
evenly spaced energy levels.

00:34:19.250 --> 00:34:21.530
You may well have seen the
results before, and you'll see

00:34:21.530 --> 00:34:24.100
it derived there.

00:34:24.100 --> 00:34:25.180
OK.

00:34:25.180 --> 00:34:31.050
Given that, then I want to
talk a little bit further

00:34:31.050 --> 00:34:33.620
about the heat capacity.

00:34:33.620 --> 00:34:39.360
So we've seen the limiting cases
for the heat capacity.

00:34:39.360 --> 00:34:42.380
Namely, the low temperature
limit is zero.

00:34:42.380 --> 00:34:45.150
That's the case whenever you
have quantized levels.

00:34:45.150 --> 00:34:49.340
You can always get kT lower
by far than the

00:34:49.340 --> 00:34:52.060
lowest excited state.

00:34:52.060 --> 00:34:54.550
So that everything is stuck
in the ground state.

00:34:54.550 --> 00:34:56.770
How low that is depends
on how far apart

00:34:56.770 --> 00:34:57.720
the states are spaced.

00:34:57.720 --> 00:35:00.350
But there's got to be some
temperature somewhere that's

00:35:00.350 --> 00:35:02.490
down there.

00:35:02.490 --> 00:35:16.310
So we've seen the heat capacity
limiting cases.

00:35:16.310 --> 00:35:36.670
Let me just sort of
draw them again.

00:35:36.670 --> 00:35:41.200
So here's kT much less
than epsilon zero.

00:35:41.200 --> 00:35:46.750
And up here, kT is much bigger
than epsilon zero.

00:35:46.750 --> 00:35:50.510
Now I'm just going to sketch
the full temperature

00:35:50.510 --> 00:35:50.990
dependence.

00:35:50.990 --> 00:35:53.130
In other words, I'm going to
connect those two limits that

00:35:53.130 --> 00:35:56.130
we've seen.

00:35:56.130 --> 00:36:14.990
So here's what that
looks like.

00:36:14.990 --> 00:36:20.600
And I'll write it
as vibrational.

00:36:20.600 --> 00:36:25.200
So we know it's got to be zero
at the low temperature limit.

00:36:25.200 --> 00:36:30.390
And we know that it's this
constant value in the high

00:36:30.390 --> 00:36:31.550
temperature limit.

00:36:31.550 --> 00:36:33.110
It's Nk.

00:36:33.110 --> 00:36:40.790
And in some way, it
smoothly connects.

00:36:40.790 --> 00:36:44.470
And if you look at the actual
scale, here -- so here's kT

00:36:44.470 --> 00:36:47.340
over epsilon zero.

00:36:47.340 --> 00:36:48.920
Here's the limit of
low temperature.

00:36:48.920 --> 00:36:52.910
Actually, you don't have to be
very high above epsilon zero

00:36:52.910 --> 00:36:55.430
to be in in this high
temperature limit.

00:36:55.430 --> 00:37:00.360
So if you look at the plot
that's on your notes, this is

00:37:00.360 --> 00:37:02.790
already -- it's not quite
leveling off precisely.

00:37:02.790 --> 00:37:04.940
But it's already pretty close.

00:37:04.940 --> 00:37:10.290
When kT is just two times
epsilon zero.

00:37:10.290 --> 00:37:22.300
It's already almost at
the limiting case.

00:37:22.300 --> 00:37:24.960
Now this has tremendous
significance.

00:37:24.960 --> 00:37:30.230
So a long time before quantum
mechanics was developed,

00:37:30.230 --> 00:37:31.760
people made measurements
of the heat

00:37:31.760 --> 00:37:34.450
capacities of materials.

00:37:34.450 --> 00:37:37.830
And they were familiar with the
fact that when you got to

00:37:37.830 --> 00:37:41.580
ordinary temperature -- room
temperature, the heat capacity

00:37:41.580 --> 00:37:45.960
was temperature independent.

00:37:45.960 --> 00:37:48.500
And that was understandable
for reasons

00:37:48.500 --> 00:37:49.990
we'll discuss shortly.

00:37:49.990 --> 00:37:55.150
Basically, in that case, the
heat capacity -- it's not just

00:37:55.150 --> 00:37:58.720
Nk for one vibrational mode.

00:37:58.720 --> 00:38:01.600
Of course, that's what I
describe for a single

00:38:01.600 --> 00:38:03.710
vibrational mode of,
say, a molecule.

00:38:03.710 --> 00:38:06.120
If you have a crystal lattice
with N atoms in it.

00:38:06.120 --> 00:38:08.440
Let's say it's an
atomic crystal.

00:38:08.440 --> 00:38:10.610
Each atom has three degrees
of freedom.

00:38:10.610 --> 00:38:14.550
It can move in each of three
independent directions.

00:38:14.550 --> 00:38:15.930
And there are N of
those atoms.

00:38:15.930 --> 00:38:18.080
There are 3N total degrees
of freedom.

00:38:18.080 --> 00:38:23.570
That's how many vibrations
the lattice has.

00:38:23.570 --> 00:38:29.070
So in fact, you have to
multiply this by 3N.

00:38:29.070 --> 00:38:34.580
So what would be seen is,
you'd have 3R, the gas

00:38:34.580 --> 00:38:38.680
constant, per mole,
in other words.

00:38:38.680 --> 00:38:44.550
And if you looked at Cv
over 3R, then this

00:38:44.550 --> 00:38:50.160
value would be one.

00:38:50.160 --> 00:38:53.290
Very useful to see that.

00:38:53.290 --> 00:38:55.250
To figure that out.

00:38:55.250 --> 00:38:56.970
And people understood it.

00:38:56.970 --> 00:39:03.190
What people didn't understand
is this stuff.

00:39:03.190 --> 00:39:06.740
Why did it do that?

00:39:06.740 --> 00:39:08.830
That was a great mystery.

00:39:08.830 --> 00:39:13.110
Why did the heat capacity go
to zero at low temperature?

00:39:13.110 --> 00:39:15.870
And the reason they didn't
understand it is because the

00:39:15.870 --> 00:39:18.980
model for vibration
was really simple.

00:39:18.980 --> 00:39:21.960
The lattice is a bunch of
masses and springs.

00:39:21.960 --> 00:39:25.060
I know the vibrational energy.

00:39:25.060 --> 00:39:26.810
And I can calculate it.

00:39:26.810 --> 00:39:31.890
That is, I know the classical
vibrational energy.

00:39:31.890 --> 00:39:35.880
Remember, the reason it
goes to zero is this.

00:39:35.880 --> 00:39:39.150
It's all because of the fact
that the energy levels are

00:39:39.150 --> 00:39:43.460
discrete, quantized levels,
with gaps in between them.

00:39:43.460 --> 00:39:47.730
If I've got classical mechanics,
then that means

00:39:47.730 --> 00:39:48.850
it's vibrational energy.

00:39:48.850 --> 00:39:51.770
The energy just gets bigger if
the amplitude get bigger.

00:39:51.770 --> 00:39:54.420
It's not discrete,
it's continuous.

00:39:54.420 --> 00:39:56.690
There are always energies
in there.

00:39:56.690 --> 00:39:59.790
In that case, there's never
a situation like this.

00:39:59.790 --> 00:40:03.600
Where kT is lower than the first
available excited level,

00:40:03.600 --> 00:40:04.650
and everything's in
the ground state.

00:40:04.650 --> 00:40:06.830
That never happens in classical
mechanics, because

00:40:06.830 --> 00:40:09.390
there are always levels there.

00:40:09.390 --> 00:40:13.250
But it does happen in
quantum mechanics.

00:40:13.250 --> 00:40:17.910
And Einstein recognized that
this was a way to explain this

00:40:17.910 --> 00:40:20.800
low temperature limiting
heat capacity.

00:40:20.800 --> 00:40:24.200
So actually if you look at early
development of quantum

00:40:24.200 --> 00:40:25.990
mechanics, really it
was all predicated

00:40:25.990 --> 00:40:28.780
on statistical mechanics.

00:40:28.780 --> 00:40:31.790
And the idea that, well, that
you could then do the

00:40:31.790 --> 00:40:35.400
statistical mechanics with
quantized levels, just the way

00:40:35.400 --> 00:40:36.260
we've done it.

00:40:36.260 --> 00:40:38.070
And what you immediately
discover is, gee,

00:40:38.070 --> 00:40:39.330
it all makes sense.

00:40:39.330 --> 00:40:43.100
You go to low temperature,
everything's stunk down here.

00:40:43.100 --> 00:40:45.160
And suddenly you've got zero
heat capacity, because you

00:40:45.160 --> 00:40:46.890
changed the temperature a little
bit, and everything is

00:40:46.890 --> 00:40:51.680
still stuck back here.

00:40:51.680 --> 00:40:56.800
So that's the vibrational heat
capacity of a solid.

00:40:56.800 --> 00:40:57.890
That's what it looks like.

00:40:57.890 --> 00:41:01.230
And at moderate temperature,
this doesn't have to be very

00:41:01.230 --> 00:41:03.280
much bigger than epsilon zero.

00:41:03.280 --> 00:41:05.410
You're already in, essentially,
the limit.

00:41:05.410 --> 00:41:06.520
The high temperature limit.

00:41:06.520 --> 00:41:12.140
And now for molecules, that
limit isn't usually reached at

00:41:12.140 --> 00:41:13.640
room temperature.

00:41:13.640 --> 00:41:20.570
Here's a kind of calibration.
kT at room temperature is

00:41:20.570 --> 00:41:27.480
about equal to 200
wave numbers.

00:41:27.480 --> 00:41:32.020
So molecular vibrations, you
know, you've taken IR spectra

00:41:32.020 --> 00:41:36.190
they're typically on the order
of 1,000 wave numbers or so.

00:41:36.190 --> 00:41:40.540
kT isn't bigger than the
vibrational energy.

00:41:40.540 --> 00:41:43.330
But a crystal lattice, you know
the vibrations are the

00:41:43.330 --> 00:41:46.560
acoustics vibrations.

00:41:46.560 --> 00:41:48.770
And those are much lower
in frequency.

00:41:48.770 --> 00:41:52.590
If you have an atomic crystal,
it just has the sound

00:41:52.590 --> 00:41:54.750
vibrations at all the different

00:41:54.750 --> 00:41:56.830
wavelengths that are available.

00:41:56.830 --> 00:41:58.890
They're never very high.

00:41:58.890 --> 00:42:01.890
So it's easy to get into
the high temperature

00:42:01.890 --> 00:42:04.700
limit, in that case.

00:42:04.700 --> 00:42:06.660
Where you basically
see a temperature

00:42:06.660 --> 00:42:14.720
independent heat capacity.

00:42:14.720 --> 00:42:15.720
OK.

00:42:15.720 --> 00:42:18.440
By the way, this was actually
used commonly to determine the

00:42:18.440 --> 00:42:20.860
molecular weights of
molecular crystals.

00:42:20.860 --> 00:42:25.060
Because you've got a factor of
the number of moles in there.

00:42:25.060 --> 00:42:26.670
If you ask how big is
the heat capacity?

00:42:26.670 --> 00:42:28.270
Well it does depend on
how many moles of

00:42:28.270 --> 00:42:29.590
material you have.

00:42:29.590 --> 00:42:31.360
Because it depends on
how many atoms.

00:42:31.360 --> 00:42:34.130
That control how many modes
there are in the crystal.

00:42:34.130 --> 00:42:35.510
How many vibrational modes.

00:42:35.510 --> 00:42:39.050
Because each atom has 3N
degrees of freedom.

00:42:39.050 --> 00:42:41.830
So if you just weigh the whole
crystal, and then you measure

00:42:41.830 --> 00:42:44.390
the heat capacity, you know how
many moles there are, and

00:42:44.390 --> 00:42:45.830
now you know the weight,
you can figure out

00:42:45.830 --> 00:42:49.660
the molecular weight.

00:42:49.660 --> 00:42:53.150
OK.

00:42:53.150 --> 00:42:54.860
So that's the low temperature
limit.

00:42:54.860 --> 00:42:57.670
And now I want to talk a little
bit further about the

00:42:57.670 --> 00:42:59.670
high temperature limit.

00:42:59.670 --> 00:43:04.510
And in particular, I want to
talk about both the heat

00:43:04.510 --> 00:43:07.510
capacity and the energy
that we've seen.

00:43:07.510 --> 00:43:11.060
Namely, this thing.

00:43:11.060 --> 00:43:14.070
Of course it's really the same
result for the energy and the

00:43:14.070 --> 00:43:14.900
heat capacity.

00:43:14.900 --> 00:43:18.720
They're obviously intimately
connected.

00:43:18.720 --> 00:43:22.340
So these are the high
temperature limits.

00:43:22.340 --> 00:43:32.470
Now it turns out that that high
temperature limit doesn't

00:43:32.470 --> 00:43:35.150
just obtain for vibrations.

00:43:35.150 --> 00:43:39.270
But it's also the case for
molecular rotations,

00:43:39.270 --> 00:43:41.680
translations.

00:43:41.680 --> 00:43:46.860
All these low energy
degrees of freedom.

00:43:46.860 --> 00:43:50.050
So let's see why.

00:43:50.050 --> 00:43:51.880
It has a name, that result.

00:43:51.880 --> 00:43:59.980
It's called the equipartition
of energy.

00:43:59.980 --> 00:44:06.760
Sometimes it's called the
classical equipartition of

00:44:06.760 --> 00:44:10.970
energy theorem.

00:44:10.970 --> 00:44:22.460
And what it says is one half
kT per degree of freedom

00:44:22.460 --> 00:44:31.040
equals energy in the
high T limit.

00:44:31.040 --> 00:44:38.440
And in particular, for
translation, so E

00:44:38.440 --> 00:44:44.390
translational is 3/2.

00:44:44.390 --> 00:44:49.900
Well, NkT for N atoms.

00:44:49.900 --> 00:44:55.250
Or molecules.

00:44:55.250 --> 00:45:00.890
E rotational is, now it depends
how many rotational

00:45:00.890 --> 00:45:02.770
degrees of freedom there are.

00:45:02.770 --> 00:45:05.170
If I've got a linear molecule,
there are only two.

00:45:05.170 --> 00:45:08.320
It can rotate this way, and
it can rotate this way.

00:45:08.320 --> 00:45:11.140
If I've got a non linear
molecule, parts all over the

00:45:11.140 --> 00:45:14.410
place, it has three
unique axes.

00:45:14.410 --> 00:45:15.890
It can also spin this way.

00:45:15.890 --> 00:45:17.880
And that's a rotational
degree of freedom.

00:45:17.880 --> 00:45:19.510
Of course the linear molecule
wasn't like that.

00:45:19.510 --> 00:45:23.340
Nothing is moving when
you do that.

00:45:23.340 --> 00:45:30.050
So it's either NkT, linear.

00:45:30.050 --> 00:45:34.120
Or 3/2 NkT.

00:45:34.120 --> 00:45:34.770
Non linear.

00:45:34.770 --> 00:45:38.560
Great.

00:45:38.560 --> 00:45:49.500
And then E vibrational is NkT
per vibrational mode.

00:45:49.500 --> 00:45:52.420
That's because vibrational
energy is potential and

00:45:52.420 --> 00:45:56.390
kinetic energy, and
it's 1/2 kT each.

00:45:56.390 --> 00:45:59.510
Why does all that
stuff happen?

00:45:59.510 --> 00:46:10.040
Turns out, you can see
why pretty easily.

00:46:10.040 --> 00:46:12.580
All those degrees of freedom.

00:46:12.580 --> 00:46:20.710
Those classical degrees
of freedom.

00:46:20.710 --> 00:46:31.400
If you say, let's write out an
expression for the energy.

00:46:31.400 --> 00:46:35.910
Classical.

00:46:35.910 --> 00:46:39.760
You know it's 1/2 m v squared.

00:46:39.760 --> 00:46:42.590
Or it's 1/2 k x squared.

00:46:42.590 --> 00:46:51.080
Or for rotational energy it's
1/2 I omega squared.

00:46:51.080 --> 00:46:52.850
You see a functional
form emerging here?

00:46:52.850 --> 00:46:56.380
That looks similar in
all these cases?

00:46:56.380 --> 00:46:59.070
You know, 1/2 times some
constant, times

00:46:59.070 --> 00:47:03.130
some variable squared.

00:47:03.130 --> 00:47:11.820
Well, now let's look at our
expressions for the energy.

00:47:11.820 --> 00:47:16.260
Average energy.

00:47:16.260 --> 00:47:21.650
We're going to sum over all the
energies of epsilon i, e

00:47:21.650 --> 00:47:25.050
to the minus Ei over kT.

00:47:25.050 --> 00:47:30.420
Over sum over i, e to the
minus Ei over kT.

00:47:30.420 --> 00:47:34.960
That's just how we originally
derived the average of energy.

00:47:34.960 --> 00:47:37.800
In other words, it's the
probability of each state

00:47:37.800 --> 00:47:39.340
times the energy
of that state.

00:47:39.340 --> 00:47:44.320
Summed up over all the states.

00:47:44.320 --> 00:47:47.560
Well, now we have an expression
for the energy.

00:47:47.560 --> 00:47:48.700
It's one of these things.

00:47:48.700 --> 00:47:53.670
It's something times
a variable squared.

00:47:53.670 --> 00:48:01.210
So, we'll use some general
functional form, a y squared.

00:48:01.210 --> 00:48:04.670
And now, let's assume we're in
the high temperature limit.

00:48:04.670 --> 00:48:06.570
And we've seen what
that means.

00:48:06.570 --> 00:48:11.060
It means kT is big,
compared to the

00:48:11.060 --> 00:48:13.580
separation between the energies.

00:48:13.580 --> 00:48:15.450
When that's the case, there
are lots of these

00:48:15.450 --> 00:48:16.580
terms in the sum.

00:48:16.580 --> 00:48:18.120
We can convert them
to integrals.

00:48:18.120 --> 00:48:20.390
We can forget about
the fact that the

00:48:20.390 --> 00:48:21.390
energies are discrete.

00:48:21.390 --> 00:48:22.400
We can say look, they're
so close

00:48:22.400 --> 00:48:26.590
together, compared to kT.

00:48:26.590 --> 00:48:29.850
That we can turn the sums
into integrals.

00:48:29.850 --> 00:48:36.680
So then we have integrals
instead of sums.

00:48:36.680 --> 00:48:37.600
And here's our energy.

00:48:37.600 --> 00:48:39.070
It's a y squared.

00:48:39.070 --> 00:48:39.930
Whatever that is.

00:48:39.930 --> 00:48:41.680
It could be this, it could be
this, it could be this.

00:48:41.680 --> 00:48:46.880
And it's not going to matter.
e to the minus a y squared

00:48:46.880 --> 00:48:54.880
over kT over, integral over e to
the minus a y squared over

00:48:54.880 --> 00:48:56.570
kT. dy, dy.

00:49:00.560 --> 00:49:03.650
OK.

00:49:03.650 --> 00:49:06.710
And here's what's
going to happen.

00:49:06.710 --> 00:49:09.280
If you do this integral
by parts.

00:49:09.280 --> 00:49:11.160
This one.

00:49:11.160 --> 00:49:16.800
What ends up happening is it
gives you this integral times

00:49:16.800 --> 00:49:19.370
a certain number.

00:49:19.370 --> 00:49:23.200
This is going to come
out of the integral.

00:49:23.200 --> 00:49:26.410
And so it will turn out.

00:49:26.410 --> 00:49:27.920
And it's straightforward
to do it.

00:49:27.920 --> 00:49:28.720
It's in the notes.

00:49:28.720 --> 00:49:29.700
It goes through.

00:49:29.700 --> 00:49:31.680
But I'll just write
the result here.

00:49:31.680 --> 00:49:35.850
The result is that you get, in
this high temperature limit

00:49:35.850 --> 00:49:42.370
where you've gone to the
integral form, you get 1/2 kT.

00:49:42.370 --> 00:49:43.790
And it will always
be the case.

00:49:43.790 --> 00:49:47.530
All you need to know is the
form of the energy.

00:49:47.530 --> 00:49:49.260
As long as that's the case --

00:49:49.260 --> 00:49:52.920
Remember y is just a variable
of integration here.

00:49:52.920 --> 00:49:56.460
That's not going to
be preserved.

00:49:56.460 --> 00:50:00.070
This comes out because
of what happens here.

00:50:00.070 --> 00:50:03.520
So what that's telling you is
whenever you have an energy of

00:50:03.520 --> 00:50:07.320
this form, and you're in the
high temperature limit, then

00:50:07.320 --> 00:50:11.860
you get this classical

00:50:11.860 --> 00:50:14.110
equipartition of energy result.

00:50:14.110 --> 00:50:16.610
So, for translation, of course
there are three separate

00:50:16.610 --> 00:50:17.770
degrees of freedom.

00:50:17.770 --> 00:50:21.300
For velocity in the x,
y, or z direction.

00:50:21.300 --> 00:50:23.640
For rotation, if it's a linear
molecule, let's say there are

00:50:23.640 --> 00:50:24.740
two separate degrees
of freedom.

00:50:24.740 --> 00:50:26.660
You have to keep track of
how many degrees of

00:50:26.660 --> 00:50:27.630
freedom there are.

00:50:27.630 --> 00:50:29.710
But that's all you have to do.

00:50:29.710 --> 00:50:31.300
That's enormously powerful.

00:50:31.300 --> 00:50:35.590
It means that without doing
anything, I know the average

00:50:35.590 --> 00:50:39.070
translational energy of the
molecules in this room.

00:50:39.070 --> 00:50:40.270
Because of course I'm certainly
in the high

00:50:40.270 --> 00:50:41.170
temperature limit.

00:50:41.170 --> 00:50:43.820
With respect to translational
energy levels, they're really

00:50:43.820 --> 00:50:45.370
closely spaced.

00:50:45.370 --> 00:50:48.250
Same with rotations.

00:50:48.250 --> 00:50:51.210
Now at room temperature
vibrations, forget it.

00:50:51.210 --> 00:50:53.950
I have essentially no
vibrational energy.

00:50:53.950 --> 00:50:57.460
I'm at the low temperature
limit for the molecular

00:50:57.460 --> 00:50:59.500
vibrations of nitrogen
or oxygen.

00:50:59.500 --> 00:51:01.700
Those are high in frequency.

00:51:01.700 --> 00:51:04.570
So much higher than
200 wavenumbers.

00:51:04.570 --> 00:51:07.990
But for each molecule,
I have 3/2 kT of

00:51:07.990 --> 00:51:09.680
translational energy.

00:51:09.680 --> 00:51:12.650
Linear molecules, I have kT
of rotational energy.

00:51:12.650 --> 00:51:14.890
Without doing any work at all.

00:51:14.890 --> 00:51:18.400
And since that applies to most
molecules at room temperature,

00:51:18.400 --> 00:51:22.390
it's an incredibly useful, very,
very general result.

00:51:22.390 --> 00:51:22.860
